The paper focuses on discovering and understanding different viewpoints in social networks, which involves analyzing social interactions and detecting descriptive terms related to different viewpoints. This aligns with several sub-categories in computer science, including social networks (cs.SOC), information retrieval (cs.IR), computational linguistics (cs.CL), cybersecurity (cs.CYBER), and social and information networks (cs.SI). However, since the paper primarily focuses on social networks and social interactions, cs.SI and cs.SOC are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.CL and cs.IR for the text analysis aspect, and cs.CYBER for the potential implications of filter bubbles and media bias on cybersecurity.
